1
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,000
I'm sorry.

2
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Mayali.

3
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Mayalino.

4
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Listen to me.

5
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Here you go.

6
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Eat, eat, my love.

7
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
With this big belly.

8
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Good boy.

9
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:21,000
With this endless eye.

10
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Nothing is left.

11
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Good boy.

12
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Good boy.

13
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Mommy!

14
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
That's a hard one, right? Chase it quickly.

15
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Last one, boy.

16
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:59,000
Alright, see time.

17
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Kingsley!

18
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Are you in love, boy?

19
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Me, sir? No, sir.

20
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
I am relieved. But then why aren't you getting on with your work?

21
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
I was going to...

22
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Where are your compasses, Kingsley?

23
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:18,000
In my desk, sir.

24
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Then get them out, boys.

25
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:25,000
Smithers, I wish you could see just how silly you look when you smirk like that.

26
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Weathersby, help him to empty out his desk.

27
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Come in.

28
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Oh, Simmons. You have a message for me, Simmons?

29
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Yes, sir. I mean, it's for Weathersby.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
He's to see the head. Right away, sir.

31
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Thank you very much.

32
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Come in.

33
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Come in.

34
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Ah, Weathersby, come in.

35
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Sit down.

36
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
All going well with the trigonometry?

37
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Yes, sir.

38
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:37,000
I've had a telephone call from your aunt, Jerome.

39
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
I'm afraid I have bad news for you.

40
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
Yes, sir.

41
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Your father has had an accident.

42
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Yes, sir.

43
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
You know your father was in Naples?

44
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Yes, sir.

45
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Your aunt heard from the hospital today.

46
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Oh.

47
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,000
It was a street accident.

48
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Yes, sir.

49
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Ah!

50
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Ah!

51
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Ah!

52
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Ah!

53
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
Ah!

54
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Ah!

55
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
Ah!

56
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Ah!

57
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,000
I'm afraid your father was very seriously hurt indeed.

58
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Yes, sir.

59
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
In fact, he died yesterday.

60
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Quite without pain.

61
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Did they shoot him through the heart?

62
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Nobody shot him, Jerome.

63
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
A pig fell on him.

64
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Your father was walking along a street in Naples

65
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
when a pig fell on him.

66
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,000
A shocking accident.

67
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Apparently, in the poorer quarters of Naples,

68
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
they keep pigs on their balconies.

69
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
This one was on the fifth floor.

70
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
It had grown too fat.

71
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:16,000
The balcony broke.

72
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
The pig fell on your father.

73
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
What happened to the pig?

74
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
It's quite a problem.

75
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
Rubbish.

76
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
Absolute rubbish.

77
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
I just have to cause them, when I told them

78
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
full details what happened,

79
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
the most extraordinary reaction was,

80
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
the most extraordinary reaction.

81
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
He asked me, um,

82
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
what happened to the pig?

83
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
What happened to the pig?

84
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Yes.

85
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Where has it been?

86
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Oh, dear.

87
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
You don't normally count this, do you?

88
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
Oh, I don't know if you cry.

89
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
I'm more a brooder.

90
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,000
Five fifteen.

91
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You're not holding it straight.

92
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Four fifteen.

93
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Why is it always fifteen?

94
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
It just is.

95
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Well...

96
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
I bet it's not real, Silver.

97
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:22,000
Yes, it is.

98
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
It was my dad's.

99
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,000
It's six fifteen.

100
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
Oh, God. Poor practice.

101
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:30,000
We'll have to make a run for it.

102
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,000
I can't.

103
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,000
Not with this.

104
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
I might drop it.

105
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,000
Hold it in your hand, then.

106
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Will it be all right?

107
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
I'd commit suicide

108
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
if that happened to my dad.

109
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Imagine it. Killed by a pig.

110
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
Never tell anyone.

111
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Please.

112
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
You promised

113
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
never to mention it.

114
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
It's a secret.

115
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Look, give the watch to me.

116
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
I won't drop it or let anything happen to it.

117
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
We've got to run.

118
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,000
I know what I'll do.

119
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
You mustn't tell anyone.

120
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
Ever.

121
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,000
I say, did you hear the story

122
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
about Wethersby?

123
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
You wouldn't be the sneak, would you, Wethersby?

124
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Or should I say pig?

125
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Why pig?

126
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Why sneak?

127
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
Who told you?

128
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,000
Who told you? I want to know.

129
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
I'm not a pig.

130
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,000
You may be a sneak, Wethersby.

131
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:16,000
I'm not.

132
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,000
If it wasn't him, leave the poor pig alone.

133
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
I want to know.

134
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:22,000
You don't seriously expect anyone to keep a secret like that, do you?

135
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
By the way, Wethersby,

136
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
a number of fellows in this club with you

137
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,000
have complained about your smell.

138
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,000
I don't smell.

139
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
I suggest you avoid the slightest odor.

140
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
It'll only make your nickname more popular, you poor soul.

141
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
Hit him, Garth! Get him!

142
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
Oh, you should! Come on!

143
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Come on, Andy!

144
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Go on, Andy!

145
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Hit him!

146
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
Go on, Andy!

147
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
Lights!

148
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Lights out.

149
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Okay. Good night.

150
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Okay. Good night.

151
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:10,000
Shut up, Wethersby.

152
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,000
I said lights out, Porter.

153
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Now, no more noise.

154
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
.

155
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:52,000
Mother's grave looks lovely in the spring time

156
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,000
with all the blossom and the fresh sea breezes.

157
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
Do you remember the stained glass in the church

158
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,000
that was broken in the storm last summer?

159
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:03,700
is exquisite. I'm so glad you like the low of democenies. I remember when I was

160
00:10:03,700 --> 00:10:07,500
your age I was tickled pink to discover there were aristocratic street gangs in

161
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:10,500
classical alleys.

162
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:35,000
Aunt Joyce? Not now Jerome. I'm busy.

163
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:44,000
I only wanted to know why father's holding an umbrella. It's not an umbrella.

164
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:50,500
It's a parasol. Your father was a very seasoned traveler. Did he always wear a

165
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:55,800
suit when he was sunbathing? And a wonderful writer. I remember when Rambles in the

166
00:10:55,800 --> 00:11:01,200
Ballyarics was first published the TLS said that you could smell the sea on

167
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:07,300
every page. Or was it the Illustrated London News?

168
00:11:07,300 --> 00:11:15,300
Now I've asked Amanda too. You like her don't you?

169
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:20,300
Come along. Answer the door. Jerome?

170
00:11:26,300 --> 00:11:42,300
I hate tea. Tea? I wouldn't say it if I didn't. I remember. It was the Courier.

171
00:11:42,300 --> 00:11:50,300
What was? The scent you could smell the sand on every page. Sand? Sea Stephen. Sea.

172
00:11:50,300 --> 00:11:55,300
My brother bought me a subscription. Such a dear little magazine it fitted into

173
00:11:55,300 --> 00:12:03,800
one's handbag. Your brother? Jerome's father. So considerate and so practical.

174
00:12:03,800 --> 00:12:13,800
Really? I hate boys as well. I remember paying 2000 lira for some mineral water

175
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:20,800
in Calabria once. Though I must say the sunsets there were really quite splendid.

176
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:28,300
Shocking accident. Was it? I can't think how such things can be allowed in a

177
00:12:28,300 --> 00:12:35,300
civilized country. I suppose one has to regard Italy as civilized. One's prepared

178
00:12:35,300 --> 00:12:41,300
for all kinds of things abroad of course. And my brother was a great traveler.

179
00:12:41,300 --> 00:12:48,800
He wrote books didn't he? I have them all. You know he was such a careful man.

180
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:54,800
What do you hate? In every way. But who could possibly have guessed as he was

181
00:12:54,800 --> 00:12:58,800
walking along the Viaduttore Emanuele Panucci on his way to the hydrographic

182
00:12:58,800 --> 00:13:04,800
museum that a pig would fall on him. What?

183
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:16,800
So what do you plan to do when you finish at school? Well I'm not bad at figures

184
00:13:16,800 --> 00:13:20,800
actually. I could go on to accountancy.

185
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:49,800
It's all a question of risk isn't it? And how you calculate it. I mean if you don't

186
00:13:49,800 --> 00:13:55,800
know the odds you can't work out the score. Now Brenda knows the score don't you

187
00:13:55,800 --> 00:14:02,800
Brenda? Oh no. I hate cricket. She knows the score all right. Enjoying your figures

188
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:10,800
Jerome? Yes thank you. Enjoy Brenda's? Brenda's what? Her figure.

189
00:14:10,800 --> 00:14:24,800
Why do you paint your nails mauve Brenda? Because it matches my eyes. It does match

190
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:31,800
my eyes doesn't it Mr. Weathersby? Brenda could you come here a moment please?

191
00:14:31,800 --> 00:14:37,800
Now's your chance Brenda. I'll leave you to it. There's some typing. If you could

192
00:14:37,800 --> 00:14:41,800
line up the figures in two columns one on the left and one on the right and the

193
00:14:41,800 --> 00:14:46,800
total time here and three copies. Yes we could have lunch while they're drying

194
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:58,800
and I don't mind working late. I have an engagement. You wouldn't like to sit down

195
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:06,800
would you? I'd love to. Oh this bed looks a bit wobbly I'm afraid. I love wobbly benches.

196
00:15:06,800 --> 00:15:21,800
And trees. Yes I like trees. And babies. Babies are adorable. Really? Do you like babies?

197
00:15:21,800 --> 00:15:28,800
Oh yes. Most men don't. At least they won't admit that they do. I expect you think I'm

198
00:15:28,800 --> 00:15:32,800
rather silly and want to talk about something like accountancy on gold. Well

199
00:15:32,800 --> 00:15:37,800
accountancy does teach one a lot about life. How? Well I mean if you look at the

200
00:15:37,800 --> 00:15:41,800
figures you'll see that this is exactly the right time for people such as

201
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:45,800
ourselves to start thinking about raising a family. I mean I think in fact...

202
00:15:45,800 --> 00:15:57,800
What can figures tell you that? Well are you sure this bench isn't a bit wobbly? Oh we can move to another one if you'd like. If you don't mind.

203
00:15:57,800 --> 00:16:09,800
Heavens no. It was a bit wobbly wasn't it? You know Jerome you're not at all like I thought you were. You're much more relaxed and easy to talk to. Good.

204
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:14,800
And when you've convinced me that figures can explain everything. Well not

205
00:16:14,800 --> 00:16:19,800
absolutely everything. I wanted to tell me all about your family.

206
00:16:25,800 --> 00:16:30,800
Did I ever tell you about my father? No.

207
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:49,800
He was killed by a pig. Really Jerome? In India? No. In Italy. I didn't realize there was pigsticking in Italy. Was your father keen on polo?

208
00:17:00,800 --> 00:17:17,800
This wine's awfully old darling. It must have been frankly pricey. Oh I'm sorry I forgot these. Let me have a melt in. Thank you. It's not like you to forget anything. Can't I kiss you? Oh sorry yes.

209
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:51,800
Have you got any of your father's books Jimmy? Aunt Joyce has got quite a few full sets. Sunshine and Shade, Nooks and Crannies and of course Rambles and the Valley Ericks. But I've got all his postcards. He used to send me one from everywhere he went. They're meant to be quite valuable now actually. You wouldn't sell any of them would you? Oh no of course not.

210
00:17:52,800 --> 00:18:14,800
Look at this. This is the watch he left it to me and it tells time to the second. See it hasn't been repaired once since. Must have been awful. I can't imagine what it would have been like if I'd lost someone when I was 12. Nine. I'm sorry I didn't know Jimmy. It must have been awful.

211
00:18:15,800 --> 00:18:37,800
I was at school when they told me. Did you take it very badly? I don't remember. I've never lost anyone. Poor Jimmy and you lost your mother. I'm sorry I'm being terribly selfish and tactless. No you're not. You're not.

212
00:18:38,800 --> 00:18:56,800
You never told me how your father died. It was a street accident. Oh dear. It was... Not another word darling. I've been awful asking all these questions. Let's eat.

213
00:18:57,800 --> 00:19:13,800
No Sally I want to. Thomas you'll never drive fast will you? We must have lots of babies with an enormous house and a huge garden and a duck pond and ducks everywhere and lilies and two donkeys.

214
00:19:13,800 --> 00:19:23,800
He was killed by a pig. Really Jerome? In India? No in Italy. I didn't realise there was pig sticking in Italy. Was your father keen on polo?

215
00:19:23,800 --> 00:19:46,800
Jimmy? Jimmy darling? You were miles away. I'm sorry I was thinking about something that happened a long time ago.

216
00:20:23,800 --> 00:20:51,800
Everything there? Yes. Is it Jimmy's father? Yes dear. How did you guess? He has Jimmy's eyes hasn't he? Quite right you know. You know I never saw it before. How clever of you.

217
00:20:51,800 --> 00:21:08,800
Shall we sit down? The tea's getting cold. Sally you may sit here. Thank you. Do you mind pouring Jerome?

218
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:24,800
It was dear to dinner won't you Sally? It's pork I hope that's alright with you. And there we... Has Jerome lent you any of his father's books? No not yet. I'll give you a set of his complete works for your wedding. Thank you.

219
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:51,800
He wrote so tenderly about his travels. I think my own favourite is nooks and crannies. He would have had a great future. Can I have a sandwich? Thank you. It made that shocking accident all the worse. Yes? Yes. I had so many letters from his readers after the pig fell on him.

220
00:21:51,800 --> 00:22:01,800
It was when he was in Naples. He was walking along the via de Torre Emanuele Panucci on his way to the high...

221
00:22:01,800 --> 00:22:10,800
Mommy! I'm back in the house!

222
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:36,800
How horrible. It makes you think doesn't it happening like that out of a clear sky.

223
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:56,800
Penny for your thoughts? I wonder what happened to the pig. They probably had it for dinner.

224
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:29,800
Thank you for watching!

